mages%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Cul%3E%5Cn%3Cli%3EChristopher%20Nolan's%20%26quot%3BOppenheimer%26quot%3B%20tells%20the%20story%20of%20who%20created%20the%20first%20atomic%20bomb.%3C%2Fli%3E%5Cn%3Cli%3EThe%20Manhattan%20Project%20required%20a%20fair%20amount%20of%20quantum%20physics%20and%20complex%20science.%3C%2Fli%3E%5Cn%3Cli%3EHere's%20a%20list%20of%20scientific%20concepts%20you%20might%20want%20to%20know%20before%20seeing%20the%20film.%3C%2Fli%3E%5Cn%3C%2Ful%3E%3Cp%3EWith%20the%20release%20of%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.insider.com%2Foppenheimer-christopher-nolan-interview-sex-scenes-barbenheimer-2023-7%5C%22%3EChristopher%20Nolan's%20%26quot%3BOppenheimer%26quot%3B%3C%2Fa%3E%C2%A0%E2%80%94%20a%20biographical%20film%20about%20the%20%26quot%3B%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Flife-career-of-j-robert-oppenheimer-father-of-atomic-bomb-2023-6%5C%22%3Efather%20of%20the%20atomic%20bomb%3C%2Fa%3E%26quot%3B%20%E2%80%94%20those%20of%20us%20who%20didn't%20pursue%20a%20career%20in%20physics%20might%20be%20feeling%20lost%20in%20the%20scientific%20concepts%20and%20jargon%20central%20to%20the%20film's%20story.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3ESo%20here's%20a%20list%20of%20the%20key%20things%20you%20might%20want%20to%20know%20before%20diving%20into%20the%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.insider.com%2Fbarbie-oppenheimer-double-feature-best-order-see-them-barbenheimer-2023-7%5C%22%3Ehighly%20anticipated%3C%2Fa%3E%C2%A0film.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch3%3EBoson%3C%2Fh3%3E%3Cp%3EA%20boson%20is%20any%20fundamental%20subatomic%20particle.%20The%20category%20includes%20photons%2C%20the%20particles%20that%20form%20light.%20The%20discovery%20of%20these%20particles%20was%20key%20to%20developing%20calutrons%2C%20described%20below%2C%20which%20allowed%20researchers%20to%20create%20the%20fuel%20needed%20for%20the%20atomic%20bomb.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch3%3ECalutrons%3C%2Fh3%3E%3Cp%3EA%20calutron%20is%20a%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fenergyeducation.ca%2Fencyclopedia%2FCalutron%5C%22%3Edevice%3C%2Fa%3E%20invented%20by%20Earnest%20O.%20Lawrence%2C%20a%20researcher%20with%20the%20Manhattan%20Project%2C%20that%20enriches%20uranium%20by%20firing%20electrons%20at%20the%20atoms%20to%20turn%20them%20into%20positively-charged%20ions.%20Once%20the%20uranium%20is%20ionized%2C%20it%20becomes%20suitable%20fuel%20for%20the%20atomic%20bomb.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3ELawrence%20modeled%20the%20calutron%20after%20his%20earlier%20device%3A%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.osti.gov%2Fopennet%2Fmanhattan-project-history%2FScience%2FParticleAccelerators%2Fcyclotron.html%5C%22%3Ethe%20cyclotron%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20a%20particle%20accelerator%20that%20%26quot%3Bshoots%26quot%3B%20particles%20in%20a%20circular%20path.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch3%3EFission%20vs.%20fusion%3C%2Fh3%3E%3Cp%3EWhile%20fission%20and%20fusion%20are%20both%20key%20components%20of%20nuclear%20technology%2C%20the%20two%20processes%20are%20very%20different%20%E2%80%94%20and%20central%20to%20the%20plot%20of%20%26quot%3BOppenheimer.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.energy.gov%2Fne%2Farticles%2Ffission-and-fusion-what-difference%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3EFission%3C%2Fa%3E%20occurs%20when%20a%20neutron%20slams%20into%20an%20atom%2C%20splitting%20its%20nucleus%20in%20half.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3ERadiochemists%20Otto%20Hahn%20and%20Fritz%20Strassman%2C%20alongside%20physicist%20Lise%20Meitner%2C%20%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.osti.gov%2Fopennet%2Fmanhattan-project-history%2FEvents%2F1890s-1939%2Fdiscovery_fission.htm%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Ediscovered%3C%2Fa%3E%20fission%20in%20Berlin%20in%201938.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EIn%20the%20film%2C%20Oppenheimer%20notes%20this%20discovery%20could%20be%20used%20to%20design%20a%20bomb%20%E2%80%94%20and%20he%20was%20right.%20This%20process%20was%20the%20basis%20for%20Oppenheimer's%20atomic%20bomb%20because%20the%20act%20of%20splitting%20an%20atom%20releases%20a%20large%20amount%20of%20energy%2C%20and%20can%20be%20accomplished%20using%20plutonium%20or%20uranium.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EMeanwhile%2C%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.energy.gov%2Fne%2Farticles%2Ffission-and-fusion-what-difference%5C%22%3Efusion%3C%2Fa%3E%20occurs%20when%20two%20atoms%20slam%20into%20one%20another%20and%20form%20one%20heavier%20atom.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EFusion%20produces%20much%20more%20energy%20than%20fission%20and%20produces%20less%20radioactive%20waste.%20However%2C%20it%20is%20difficult%20to%20make%20happen%20because%20the%20process%20requires%20extreme%20amounts%20of%20pressure%20and%20high%20temperatures.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20hydrogen%20bomb%20%E2%80%94%20promoted%20by%20Lewis%20Strauss%2C%20a%20member%20of%20the%20US%20Atomic%20Energy%20Commission%20%E2%80%94%20relies%20on%20fusion%2C%20making%20it%20far%20more%20powerful%20than%20the%20atomic%20bomb.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch3%3ELight%C2%A0%3C%2Fh3%3E%3Cp%3EIn%20the%20film%2C%20Oppenheimer%20says%20light%20has%20properties%20of%20both%20particles%20and%20waves.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20famous%20double-slit%20experiment%20confirmed%20this%20finding.%20During%20the%20test%2C%20photons%20were%20fired%20at%20a%20sensor%20screen%20through%20two%20slits.%20This%20experiment%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.discovery.com%2Fscience%2FDouble-Slit-Experiment%5C%22%3Edemonstrated%3C%2Fa%3E%20that%20when%20photons%20are%20being%20observed%2C%20they%20behave%20like%20particles.%20But%20when%20they%20are%20not%20observed%2C%20photons%20behave%20like%20waves.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3ETo%20this%20day%2C%20that%20discrepancy%20remains%20a%20mystery%20in%20the%20field%20of%20quantum%20mechanics.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch3%3ENew%20Physics%3C%2Fh3%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BNew%20Physics%26quot%3B%20is%20a%20term%20that%20describes%20the%20rapid%20evolution%20of%20discoveries%20in%20the%20field%20of%20physics%20during%20the%20mid-%20to%20late-20th%20century.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EIn%20particular%2C%20this%20movement%20included%20the%20development%20of%20quantum%20mechanics%2C%20a%20field%20that%20proved%20essential%20to%20Oppenheimer's%20pursuit%20because%20it%20enabled%20researchers%20to%20create%20tools%20like%20the%20calutron%2C%20as%20well%20as%20understand%20the%20mechanics%20of%20fission%20and%20fusion.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch3%3ERadioactive%20isotopes%3C%2Fh3%3E%3Cp%3E%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fehss.energy.gov%2Fohre%2Froadmap%2Fachre%2Fintro_9_4.html%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3ERadioactive%20isotopes%3C%2Fa%3E%20are%20essential%20for%20the%20fusion%20and%20fission%20reactions%20that%20power%20nuclear%20weapons.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EEach%20element%20has%20a%20set%20number%20of%20neutrons%2C%20protons%2C%20and%20electrons%20that%20define%20it.%20A%20radioactive%20isotope%2C%20aka%20radioisotope%2C%20has%20a%20different%20number%20of%20neutrons%20but%20the%20same%20number%20of%20protons%2C%20making%20its%20nucleus%20unstable%20and%20thus%20more%20reactive.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EU-238%20is%20the%20most%20stable%2C%20and%20thus%20most%20commonly%20occurring%2C%20form%20of%20uranium.%20U-235%20has%20three%20fewer%20neutrons%20and%20is%20the%20more%20reactive%20form%20of%20uranium%20used%20in%20nuclear%20bombs%20and%20nuclear%20reactors.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3ERadioisotopes%20became%20wrapped%20in%20%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov%2Fpmc%2Farticles%2FPMC2923454%2F%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Epolitical%20controversy%3C%2Fa%3E%20after%20the%20war%20ended.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EOppenheimer%20led%20a%20group%20of%20physicists%20who%20advocated%20for%20the%20United%20States%20to%20export%20radioactive%20isotopes%20to%20researchers%20abroad.%20He%20argued%20that%20the%20United%20States%20would%20improve%20global%20welfare%20by%20making%20the%20materials%20democratically%20available.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EHowever%2C%20Strauss%20pushed%20back%20while%20serving%20as%20chair%20of%20the%20US%20Atomic%20Energy%20Commissio